  1. Install two packages gganimate and gifski then restart Rstudio. Using the Adult Census Income data, make an animation using geom_point and transition_states.
library(gganimate)
library(gifski)
library(readr)
library(ggplot2)
library(tidyverse)

df <- read_csv('adult_census.csv')

df %>% ggplot(aes(x = hours.per.week, y = capital.loss, color = sex )) + 
      geom_point() + 
      transition_states(race) + 
      labs(title = 'Race = {closest_state}')

  1. Using the Adult Census Income data, make an animation using geom_bar and transition_states.
df %>% ggplot(aes(x = sex, fill = race)) + 
      geom_bar(position = 'fill') + 
      transition_states(marital.status) + 
      labs(title = 'Marital Status = {closest_state}')

  1. Use the WHO’s dataset at this link. Make a top-10 bar race by months between countries on the number of deaths by Covid 19 in 2021.
df <- read_csv('https://covid19.who.int/WHO-COVID-19-global-data.csv')

library(tweenr)
library(lubridate)

df$month <- month(df$Date_reported)
df$year <- year(df$Date_reported)

d1 <- df %>% filter(year == 2021) %>% 
      group_by(month, Country) %>% 
      summarize(sum = sum(New_deaths))
      
p1 <- d1 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = sum, y = Country)) + 
  geom_col() + 
  transition_states(month) + 
  labs(x = 'Total Deaths', y = 'Country', title = 'Month: {closest_state}')

d2 <- d1 %>% 
  group_by(month) %>% 
  mutate(rank=rank(-sum))

d3 <- d2 %>% filter(rank <= 10)

p1 <- d3 %>% 
  ggplot(aes(y=factor(rank), 
             x=sum, group=Country, 
             fill=Country)) + 
  geom_col()+
  transition_states(month)+
  labs(x = 'Total Deaths', 
       title = 'Month: {closest_state}') + 
  ease_aes("cubic-in-out")

animate(p1, nframes=400)

  1. Make a bar race using a dataset of your own interest. You may use the dataset that we use in class (https://covidtracking.com/data/download/all-states-history.csv) but you should make a different bar racev from ones in the slides.
df <- read_csv('all-states-history.csv')

df$week <- week(df$date)
d1 <- df %>% group_by(week, state) %>% summarise(mean = mean(hospitalizedCurrently))
d2 <- d1 %>% group_by(week) %>% mutate(rank=rank(-mean)) 
d3 <- d2 %>% filter(rank <= 10)

a1 <- d3 %>% ggplot(aes(x=rank, y=mean, group=state, fill=state, label=state)) + 
  geom_col()+ 
  labs(title = 'Week {closest_state}', x='', y='Total Number of Positive Caeses', fill='state') + 
  transition_states(week)+ 
  ease_aes("cubic-in-out")

animate(a1, nframes = 200)
